article.headline: San Francisco 62, Santa Clara 60
article.story: SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Alan Wiggins' 15-foot baseline jumper with six-tenths of a second remaining lifted San Francisco to a 62-60 victory over Santa Clara on Thursday night. Wiggins, who hadn't made a basket since midway through the second half, took a pass from Andre Hazel and sank the game-winning shot to stun the Broncos in what was just the Dons' third road win of the season. John Cox scored 21 points to lead San Francisco (13-6, 4-2 West Coast Conference), while Tyrone Riley added 17 points and seven rebounds. The Dons have now won four straight after dropping their first two conference games of the year. Travis Niesen scored 15 points to lead Santa Clara. Doron Perkins had 14 points, seven rebounds and seven assists for the Broncos (11-10, 4-2), whose four-game winning streak came to an end. San Francisco is undefeated at home this season, but was just 2-6 on the road. The Dons led for most of the game but went cold late in the second half, allowing the Broncos to come back from a nine-point deficit to tie the game on a 3-pointer from Perkins with 1:10 left to play. San Francisco missed two shots in the final minute before Hazel found Wiggins standing alone along the left baseline. Wiggins, who finished with 11 points and eight rebounds, then calmly hit the game-winner. Cox hit seven of his first eight shots, scoring 16 points in the first half to help the Dons to a 35-30 lead. Santa Clara rallied from seven points down to take a brief lead late in the first half before Cox scored six straight points to put San Francisco back in charge.
